  "id": "019cf625-7dd3-7a72-90bd-3749af7e2b73",
  "content": "<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n<meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n<title>LinkedIn Post - DaVinci Resolve on Linux</title>\n<style>\n  body {\n    font-family: -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, sans-serif;\n    max-width: 680px;\n    margin: 40px auto;\n    padding: 24px;\n    font-size: 16px;\n    line-height: 1.6;\n    color: #1a1a1a;\n    background: #fff;\n  }\n  p { margin: 0 0 1em 0; }\n  .instructions {\n    background: #f0f4ff;\n    border: 1px solid #c0d0ff;\n    border-radius: 8px;\n    padding: 16px;\n    margin-bottom: 24px;\n    font-size: 14px;\n    color: #445;\n  }\n  hr { border: none; border-top: 1px solid #ddd; margin: 24px 0; }\n  #post { cursor: text; }\n</style>\n</head>\n<body>\n\n<div class=\"instructions\">\n  <strong>How to use:</strong> Select all text below the line, copy (Ctrl+C), and paste directly into LinkedIn's post editor. Line breaks will be preserved.\n</div>\n\n<hr>\n\n<div id=\"post\">\n<p>A few days ago I moved my desktop to Linux. Lower RAM baseline, native Docker, GPU assignment with DRI_PRIME. The engineering benefits were clear. But the real test was creative work.</p>\n\n<p>So I installed DaVinci Resolve on Ubuntu 24.04 for the first time.</p>\n\n<p>It didn't go smoothly. Dependency conflicts, library mismatches, things that should just work on a fresh Ubuntu install but don't. Most of the issues traced back to the same root causes: Wayland and Ubuntu 24.04 specifics that Resolve doesn't expect.</p>\n\n<p>I would have given up. But I had Claude.</p>\n\n<p>Every wall I hit, Claude read the error, searched for known issues, and wrote the fix. Each fix revealed the next issue. Wayland kept being the common thread.</p>\n\n<p>Then came the one that almost beat us both.</p>\n\n<p>Resolve threw \"GPU memory is full\" with black playback. Claude initially diagnosed it as an out-of-memory issue and we started building a proxy pipeline to work around it. But something didn't add up. I dug deeper and steered us back to the debug logs.</p>",
